pr_body: Final PR for issue #43 (https://github.com/opencax/GSoC/issues/43) as part of GSoC 2022.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1016252952, 'comment_body': 'This probably needs to be removed or made configurable.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 8, 7, 58, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1016254889, 'comment_body': 'This is an interesting if statement. Is that `if len(file.by_type("IfcBuilding")) == 0`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 8, 8, 0, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1016259587, 'comment_body': "This variable appears not to be read.

In general, `set`s would be more appropriate for this kind of things. You don't depend on the order of the list and sets are much more efficient to check for containment. They don't have duplicates and allow for easy removal of elements also.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 8, 8, 4, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1016261407, 'comment_body': "For now it's fine to center around buildings. But for the future it'd be good to also allow other infra-related spatial structure elements, such as IfcBridge. Maybe make a comment regarding that.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 8, 8, 6, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1016262447, 'comment_body': 'Strictly speaking filenames do not need to have an extension. Did you meant checking something like `not os.path.isdir()`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 8, 8, 7, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1016268398, 'comment_body': 'Why `hash(self)` and not just `self`? This generates collisions. dicts are are hash maps, so you don't need to manually hash the key. Internally in a hash map the hash is used to determine the "bucket" the value will go into, but there will still be actual equality testing within the bucket. As the hash is not necessarily unique.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 8, 8, 14, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1017279907, 'comment_body': ' in this case yes. It was a way to check if index exists without throwing an IndexError', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 9, 0, 58, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mdjska', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1017280269, 'comment_body': "Yea, I know files don't need extensions, but since there are no other checks of overwriting/validity, I made the assumption that if there is an extension the written path was conscious. Since os.path.isdir() of an 'invalid' path will return false. But I wrote this for the write_file node, where the user can actually give raw input paths. The file picker pop-up window in the panel, makes the whole operation much safer, so maybe it can be deleted/changed.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 9, 0, 59, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mdjska', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1017283195, 'comment_body': 'In short, hash(self) was the only number/ID that I could find was, and stayed, unique for each node instance. Sverchok uses the `node_id` attribute internally, which is also based on hash(self) (https://github.com/nortikin/sverchok/issues/2445). And I don't remember exactly why right now, but I had some issues with that attribute either not staying unique or changing during the life time of the node, but didn't have the same issues with using hash(self) directly. I would have to test it again.
I'm not sure how you would do it with just `self`? The issue with not having an internal node_dict was, that two nodes of the same type (Eg. two "IFC By Type" nodes) will not make new class instances, but both use the same one, so stored information would leak from one node to another. If you have an idea on how this can be handled differently, I'd like to change it. Not sure if the problem mentioned [here](https://github.com/nortikin/sverchok/issues/3564#issuecomment-695770526) also applies?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 9, 1, 5, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mdjska', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1018758734, 'comment_body': "That approach there would indeed not stay unique as it explicitly `xor`s in the current time. I'm also not sure how authoritative that post is. You can see explained here what the relationship is between id() [what internally would be used when you use `self`] and hash() for types that don't override __hash__ https://stackoverflow.com/a/33572401 Python may recycle ids when they are disposed so that's why they factor in the current time. But the problem remains. I still think `self` here is better than `hash(self)`. If you want a numeric ID, the proper way would probably be a globally defined auto incrementing counter https://stackoverflow.com/a/1045724

Anyway this is a bit of a rabbit hole. I'm fine if we keep it like this. Just wanted to provide some bg info. I'll mark this as resolved.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 11, 10, 7, 59, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'aothms', 'type': 'User'}]
